{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/simulation-of-the-linear-regression-model-with-autocorrelated-errors-b5606186f406", "time": 1683017990.076923, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/simulation-of-the-linear-regression-model-with-autocorrelated-errors-b5606186f406/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Simulation of the Linear Regression Model with Autocorrelated Errors | by Audhi Aprilliant | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Simulation of the Linear Regression Model with Autocorrelated Errors", "description": "Autocorrelation is a type of serial dependence. It may exist in a regression model when the order of the observations in the data is relevant or time-series"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/6407474.pdf", "anchor_text": "The Linear Regression Model with Autocorrelated Errors: Just Say No to Error Autocorrelation", "paragraph_index": 14}, {"url": "http://audhiaprilliant.github.io/", "anchor_text": "http://audhiaprilliant.github.io/", "paragraph_index": 16}], "all_paragraphs": ["Linear Regression is a technique in which studying the linear relationship and the influence between the dependent and independent variable in a data set. The X is the matrix of the independent variable, y is the vector of the dependent variable.", "The linear regression has two regression coefficients as follows.", "Because linear regression is a stochastic technique, we may find that there are usually errors. The aim of linear regression is to minimize these errors using ordinary least squares (OLS).", "In order to conclude and interpret the linear regression equation, there are a few assumptions that must be fulfilled. If those are not fulfilled, the linear regression will be not valid.", "Autocorrelation means the relationship between each value of errors in the equation. Or in the other hand, autocorrelation means the self relationship of errors. This assumption is popularly found in time-series data.", "To identify the effect of autocorrelation in the linear regression model, we should generate and compare two cases: linear regression that violates the autocorrelation assumption and linear regression that doesn\u2019t violate the autocorrelation assumption. In this case, another assumption is ignored and assumed that they are fulfilled. The simulation is generated 1000 times with rules as follows.", "Note: to make us easier to understand the concept of autocorrelation and will not be confused by the terms or symbols, alpha is the regression coefficients without autocorrelation and beta is the regression coefficients with autocorrelation. Further, the subscript null will be named as intercept and the one as slope", "The coefficient \u03c1 is called the first-order autocorrelation coefficient and takes values from -1 to +1. Theoretically, it determines the autocorrelation effect in the simulation. There can be three different cases.", "The previous rule to generate the simulation is properly translated into the R script as follows. To modify the sequence of the autocorrelation coefficient, you can easily edit the script in the 58th line. Otherwise, the number of observations and repetition also can be modified by editing the script in the 59th line.", "When you run the dim(df), it should print the dimension of 21,000 rows indicating the number of the autocorrelation sequence which is 21 values. It is used to compare the mean and standard deviation for various autocorrelation coefficients.", "Further, the df should be reshaped from wide format to long format to create data visualization using ggplot2. It aims to create a column that contains the coefficient names (intercept or slope).", "Now, the data with a long format is ready to use for data viz. We create a new column of Status to separate the intercept and slope for the next analysis.", "The data which is generated using data aggregation displays the mean and standard deviation for both intercept and slope. However, that is not good for our conclusion so that we create a data viz using boxplot.", "Although the parameter estimators will be unbiased, there are serious consequences that might happen when our linear regression model does not fulfill the autocorrelation assumption like the linear regression conclusion or interpretation will be not valid because it is no longer have a minimum variance estimator.", "[1] A. McGuirk, A. Spanos. 2002. The Linear Regression Model with Autocorrelated Errors: Just Say No to Error Autocorrelation. Annual Meeting of the American Agricultural Economics Association, July 28\u201331, 2002.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Data Scientist. Tech Writer. Statistics, Data Analytics, and Computer Science Enthusiast. Portfolio & social media links at http://audhiaprilliant.github.io/"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fb5606186f406&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fsimulation-of-the-linear-regression-model-with-autocorrelated-errors-b5606186f406&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fsimulation-of-the-linear-regression-model-with-autocorrelated-errors-b5606186f406&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-------